		<article>
			<h1 class="storytitle"><a href="http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=157" rel="bookmark">Another voice against CAPTCHA</a></h1>

			<div class="post-text">
				<p>I tried to leave a comment on <a href="http://www.digg.com/">Digg</a> recently and had trouble deciphering its <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captcha">CAPTCHA</a>. I was eventually successful, but only after I got annoyed. Simply put, CAPTCHAs are evil.</p>
<p>There&#8217;s no need to rehash why, since <a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=captcha+accessibility">plenty</a> has been said so far. They <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/turingtest/">don&#8217;t</a> really work and they <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captcha#Accessibility">exclude</a> lots of people even if you do use an alternative audio check. As a left-handed person, who curses every time he picks up an &#8220;ergonomically&#8221; designed scissors, I kind of imagine how it is when things are designed for a majority you don&#8217;t belong to.</p>
<p>However, even if you could make them completely accessible (doubtful) and would somehow be able to resolve the overlap between smartest programs and, well, less-gifted humans (impossible), I&#8217;d still dislike them. What they say to your readers is: &#8220;I&#8217;ll make you work so I don&#8217;t have to.&#8221;</p>
<p>Is this the message you want to communicate?</p>
<p>P.S: WordPress users, you really ought to take a look at <a href="http://akismet.com/">Akismet</a>, if you haven&#8217;t done so.</p>
			</div>

			<footer class="post-metadata">
